The paper discusses techniques for effective coordination of agents' actions in partially-observable domains, which is a major challenge in multi-agent systems research. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.MA (Multiagent Systems) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of machine learning algorithms for learning estimates of the states and actions of other agents, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-categories. The paper proposes a novel information-sharing protocol for the distribution of state information, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category. Finally, the paper evaluates its proposed strategy in a simulated call-routing application, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) sub-category.
